|/table

---

## Derivational Morphology

|table
morph | meaning | source
- | - | -
ak- | tool | "do"
akta- | collection | "many"
da- | causative | "reason"
ik- | diminutive | "small"
pat- | person who | "write"
pok- | augmentative | "enlarge"
pipti- | adjective | "similarity"
|/table

The ik- diminutive has a negative connotation. Think shriveled or scrawny.

The pok- augmentative has a positive connotation. Think well-fed or chubby.

The adjectival prefix is typically only added to a stem when it is of higher animacy than the lexical noun.

---

## Verb Markers

|table
mark | etymology | verb form | gloss
- | - | -
ak- | a:ka | agentive | by
bi- | b:ik | perfect | action is completed
bo- | bo:ki | inessive | within
da- | d:ap | causative | causes
gi- | gi:ta | objective | takes additional patient argument
ik- | i:ki | reflexive | -self
kaada- | k:agh d:ap | prohibitive | do not
-khai | ikh:ai | irrealis | perhaps
khi- | khi:ka | negative | does not
kot- | kot:oki | benefactive | for
oki- | oki:pih | locative | at
paa- | pa:ta | double passive | takes no S or DO; old IO is new S
pi- | pipi:ti | comitative | along with
ti- | t:ikh | triple passive | takes no S, DO, or IO
toak- | to:gih a:ka | reversive | swaps S with DO
togh- | to:gih | instrumental | by means of
too- | to:gih | passive | takes no S; old DO is new S
tooda- | to:gih d:ap | imperative | do
|/table

The passive, imperative, and negative imperative change the stem verb to its noun form.

The double and triple passive, which indicate the verb takes two or three less arguments respectively, change the stem to its indefinite form.

